  h3 Card Overlay

  p The class #[code .card__overlay] can be used to insert a block of (e.g. text) on a layer over the other content within the card (e.g. over the image).
    
  .flexbox.flexbox--gap.flexbox--nested
    .flex-item-md--span-4
      p #[code .card__overlay--top]
      
      .card.decorate(style="max-width: 400px")
        a(href="#/").card__image
          +image-placeholder-light(400, 400)
        .card__overlay.card__overlay--top
          | Card overlay text (top)

    .flex-item-md--span-4
      p #[code .card__overlay--middle]
      
      .card.decorate(style="max-width: 400px")
        a(href="#/").card__image
          +image-placeholder-light(400, 400)
        .card__overlay.card__overlay--middle
          | Card overlay text (middle)
                
    .flex-item-md--span-4
      p #[code .card__overlay--bottom]
      
      .card.decorate(style="max-width: 400px")
        a(href="#/").card__image
          +image-placeholder-light(400, 400)
        .card__overlay.card__overlay--bottom
          | Card overlay text (bottom)

  p Notes on usage of the card overlay:

  ol
    li.
      The card overlay must have less/smaller content than the other content that it is overlaying. (In these examples above: an image is being overlayed by text &ndash; too much text would stick out beyond the image.)
    li.
      If you need to use the card overlay with the header header and/or footer, be aware of the fact that the overlay will overlay the header and/or footer too. If this is a problem for your design, then you need to #[b add an extra container around the overlay], and give it CSS #[code position: relative]. (But exclude the header and/or footer from this extra container.)

  h3 Cards with Constrained Height
  
  p If the height of a card is constrained (by a stated height on itself or on a container), then the #[code .card__body] has auto overflow scrolling (vertical).
    
  .flexbox.flexbox--center
    .flex-item-sm--span-6
      .card.card--vertical.decorate(style="height: 345px; max-width: 400px")
        .card__header
          | Header
        .card__body
          h4 Card Title
          +paragraph(4)
        .card__footer
          | Footer
      
  p #[b Note:] #[code .card__section] does not have this same behavior.  

  h3 Cards can be Nested
    
  p There may be some circumstances where you need to "nest" cards &ndash; or place smaller card(s) "inside" a bigger card. As Codebase cards are media objects, you would expect to be able to do this and you can, easily. 
  
